<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-642-190  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 642 190.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 24 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>General Motors to build satellite networks for dealers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Motors Corp. (communication systems).andO;Ticker:    GM.andO;Topic:     Automobile IndustrySatellite Communications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GENERAL MOTORS TO BUILD SATELLITE NETWORK FOR DEALERS DETROIT, MICHIGAN,U.S.A., 1990 MAY 21 (NB) -- Following the lead of its domestic competitors,General Motors announced it will build a satellite communications network forits 9,700 car and truck dealers in the U.S.andP;  The &quot;GM Pulsat Network&quot; -- willplace a satellite dish on each GM dealership for information exchange with GMdivisions.andM;The company said this is the largest such network in the world, in keepingwith the fact that GM is the U.S.andP;  largest company.andP;  GM will fully fundinstallation of the network.andP;  Test installations will begin this summer andthe target for completing the system is late 1992.andM;The network will be installed by two GM subsidiaries, the computer-servicesfirm Electronic Data Systems, and the satellite firm GM Hughes Electronics.andO;As part of the network, Hughes will install a 6-foot diameter satellite dishat each GM dealership.andM;&quot;With the GM Pulsat Network, we'll be able to exchange information in a fewseconds on vehicle ordering, warranty and service data, and dozens of othersubjects which often require an overnight message on the current system,&quot;said a GM spokesman.andP;  The network will also handle transmission of shopmanuals, vehicle invoicing and vehicle diagnostics, as well as videoconferences on new products and employee training.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900522/Press Contact: Harold Jackson, General MotorsCorporation, 313-556-2032)</TEXT></DOC>